The LMDI method is based on the well-established Kaya identity that decomposes the energy-related CO2 emissions into four factors: per capita income, energy intensity per unit of GDP, carbon intensity (emissions per unit of energy consumption), and population (Kaya, 1989). The Kaya identity can be expressed as7\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{CO}}_{2}=\left(\frac{\mathrm{GDP}}{\mathrm{Population}}\right)*\left(\frac{\mathrm{EC}}{\mathrm{GDP}}\right)*\left(\frac{{\mathrm{CO}}_{2}}{\mathrm{EC}}\right)*(\mathrm{Population})$$\end{document}CO2=GDPPopulation∗ECGDP∗CO2EC∗(Population)

In this study, we seek to extend the well-established Kaya identity by adding the energy structure effect. Resultantly, Eq. 7 has the following form:8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
